Metal nanostructure like silver, gold and copper are readily synthesized by using various parts of plant extracts (seed, stem, leaf, flower, fruit and gum). Owing to the high reduction potential, these metal ions could be easily reduced by organic compounds, especially polyphenols present in extracts. There is no need for any additional chemical reducing agent. Moreover, organic molecules exist in extracts also act stabilizing agents. Metal nanoparticles absorb ultraviolet and visible light owing to surface plasmon resonance and inter-band transition properties. In case of metal nanoparticles, sp-band electrons are excited by absorption of suitable light. Also, surface plasmon effect leads hot electrons, which reduce oxygen molecules and form oxygen free radicals. The holes generated in the sp-band will oxidize water to form hydroxyl radicals. These radicals can degrade organic pollutants in water (Fig. 4
                        ). For instance, Au nanostructures (hexagonal, truncated triangular and spherical morphology) are readily synthesized by using Lagerstroemia speciosa leaf extract (Choudhary et al., 2017). The completion of Au3+ reduction takes 30 min at 25 °C while at 80 °C, only 2 min are enough. These Au nanostructures could be used as photocatalyst for photo-reduction of different organic compounds (4-nitrophenol, bromocresol green, methylene blue, methyl orange, and bromophenol blue) with aid of (3 × 10−2 mol L−1) NaBH4 and sun light illumination. In this case, surface plasmon resonance effect and BH4
                        − and/or H− layer involved in the reduction of selected organic pollutants. Upon exposure of light, adsorbed hydride layer produces hydrogen molecules while hot electrons are accumulated in the conduction band of Au nanoparticles. Karthik et al. have reported synthesis of Ag spheres using Camellia japonica leaves extract (Karthik et al., 2017). About 10 mg of Ag nanospheres shows 97% of photocatalytic efficiency for photodegradation of (75 mL, 10 mg L−1) eosin Y in aqueous solution under 60 min of visible light irradiation. Recently, Phaseolus vulgaris seeds which possess phenolic compounds, vitamins, flavonoids, antioxidants and proteins have been used for preparation of more stable metallic silver nanospheres with the size range of 10–20 nm. About 5 mg of Ag nanospheres was used for photocatalytic degradation of 20 mg L−1 (50 mL) of aqueous reactive red-141 dye solution which is relatively stable than methylene blue. This experiment was performed under direct sunlight irradiation (flux = 645 W m−2) for 150 min. The reactive red-141 dye degradation efficiency and quantum efficiency are 97% and 3.68 × 10−6 molecule photon−1 (Rania et al., 2020). In another report, Portulaca oleracea leaves extract which contains alkaloids, flavonoids, tannins, and saponins was used for reduction of Ag+ ions. This extract forms silver nanoparticles within 20 min of reaction time. The synthesized (10 mg) Ag nanoparticles effectively decolorize the (50 mL) 10 mg L−1 concentration of reactive green 19A (100%), reactive blue 59 (85%), reactive red 120 (88%), reactive 141 (90%) and reactive red 2 (80%) under ultraviolet exposure (UV-A, λ = 365 nm; 1000 μW cm−2) for 60 min (Saratale et al., 2020).

Chitosan is an abundant polysaccharide which is not soluble in most of the organic solvents and water. However, it dissolves in dilute acids such as acetic acid. It possesses numerous amino (-NH2) and hydroxyl (-OH) groups which act as active sites that exhibit excellent chelation and electrostatic interaction properties. It favours adsorption of pollutants in water and immobilization of inorganic nanoparticles (Rani et al., 2020). Further, it is relatively cheap and biocompatible material. It also inherently exhibits antimicrobial property. These desirable properties make it a potential counterpart in photocatalytic material which is used in the water treatment. Incorporation of inorganic nanoparticles in chitosan further enhances its antimicrobial activity. For example, chitosan-MnFe2O4 binary nanocomposite was prepared and used as antibacterial agent against P. aeruginosa and E. coli. Mansur et al. (2014) have prepared ZnS/chitosan composite for photocatalytic decomposition of methylene blue and methyl orange in water under ultraviolet illumination. Compared to bulk ZnS (3.61 eV), the optical band gap of ZnS/chitosan is slightly (3.92 eV) high. It denotes that chitosan can also be reducing band gap of semiconductor nanoparticles which facilitate production of active free radicals (Fig. 6
                        ). However, this composite shows greater photocatalytic degradation efficiency to the selected pollutant due to its greater charge separation efficiency and surface area. Table 3
                         shows list of recently reported chitosan based photocatalyst and their performances (Nawaz et al., 2020; Balakrishnan et al., 2020; Vanamudan et al., 2018; Vigneshwaran et al., 2019, 2020; Narayanan et al., 2020; Nithya et al., 2017; Gupta et al., 2017; Aziz et al., 2020; Ali et al., 2020; Aadnan et al., 2020; Preethi et al., 2020; Shaha et al., 2020; Cao et al., 2017; Shoueir et al., 2018, 2019; Alhokbany et al., 2020; Li et al., 2019; Yang et al., 2021b; Zarei et al., 2020; Eskandari et al., 2020). Chitosan has also been used for preparation of ternary (Shaha et al., 2020; Cao et al., 2017; Shoueir et al., 2018, 2019; Alhokbany et al., 2020) and quaternary (Li et al., 2019; Yang et al., 2021b; Zarei et al., 2020; Eskandari et al., 2020) nanocomposite photocatalysts.

Hydroxyapatite is a calcium phosphate inorganic biomaterial with stoichiometric form of Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2. It has great adsorption capacity, ion-exchange capability and thermal stability (Du et al., 2021). There are few reports on photocatalytic activity of pure hydroxyapatite. Liu et al. (2016) have synthesized hydroxyapatite nanospheres by using wet chemical synthesis method. The hydroxyapatite nanospheres show 93% of methyl orange degradation efficiency within 120 min under ultraviolet illumination. Later (Edralin et al., 2017), it has been reported that hydroxyapatite nanorods synthesized using mussel shells shows 86.8% for rhodamine B aqueous solution under ultraviolet irradiation (20 W; λ
                        max = 254 nm). Perhaps hydroxyapatite based composites have been synthesized to achieve higher photocatalytic performance. Compared to semiconductor photocatalysts, hydroxyapatite is a poorer photocatalyst. However, due to its biocompatibility and availability, efforts have been devoted to produce highly active hydroxyapatite photocatalysts (Table 4
                        ) (Brazon et al., 2016; Tanji et al., 2020; Ekka et al., 2018; Bharath and Ponpandian, 2015; Mondal et al., 2017; Xu et al., 2019; Chang et al., 2016, 2017; Zou et al., 2020a, 2020b; Piccirillo et al., 2015; Zhang et al., 2015; Vigneshwaran et al., 2021; Alorku et al., 2020).
